<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n12042m"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n12" href="#n12042m">N12 (VI.B.14)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n12all.htm#n12042m"> 42(m)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> boat of hide / fettered feet / key in sea / drifts to Man</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">The perfect convert, MacCuil, anxious to do penance for his sins, inquired what he was to do; and St. Patrick ordered him to quit his native country, taking nothing with him except a coarse habit, and going to sea in a leathern boat, without oar or rudder, to serve God in the first place where the winds would land him. He obeyed, and the wind and frail bark landed him in the Isle of Man <font color="green">[&hellip;]</font> We give the narrative in the graphic words of the Book of Armagh: &ldquo;<font color="green">[&hellip;]</font> Do you, therefore, depart now, unarmed, to the sea <font color="green">[&hellip;]</font> and when you reach the sea, bind your feet together with an iron fetter, and cast the key of it into the sea, and set out in a boat of one hide, without rudder or oar, and wherever the wind and sea shall lead you, be prepared to remain <font color="green">[&hellip;]</font>&rdquo; <small> Very Rev. Dean Kinane, <a name="TKSP" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#TKSP"><cite title="source">St. Patrick: his life, his heroic virtues, his labours, and the fruits of his labours</cite></a>, (ed. unknown) 152-5</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
